
    DURBAN yesterday kicked off another conference that brought hundreds of international guests to the country.The Terminal Operators Conference was held at the Inkosi Albert Luthuli International Convention Centre.Speaking at the conference, President Jacob Zuma said Durban and KZN were gateways to the country and Africa.He said the province contributed to the economy through its two busiest ports, Durban and Richards Bay.The two-day conference is expected to bring together experts and investors involved in:logisticsliner shippingportsterminalsinland transportmanufacturingThey will discuss improving trade flows across Africa.“Over 90% of trade in Africa occurs by sea,” said Zuma.“Durban and Richards Bay are the busiest ports in the southern hemisphere.“This alone positions KZN as a trade gateway to the country and entire Africa.”The conference would contribute towards promoting and highlighting the infrastructure of the country’s ports, particularly those in KZN.KZN Economic Development, Tourism and Environmental Affairs MEC Sihle Zikalala echoed Zuma’s sentiment: “The conference will also showcase to the world the vast array of investment opportunities and capabilities on offer at the world-class ports, which also have an established history as the gateway into Africa.”Transnet CEO Siyabonga Gama said means were continuously being made to improve ports infrastructure.if(typeof za24_DisplayAd != "undefined") za24_DisplayAd("300x250","2");var viewReq = new Array();function vu(u) {var i=new Image();i.src=u.replace("&amp;","&");viewReq.push(i);}vu("https://securepubads.g.doubleclick.net/pcs/view?xai\x3dAKAOjssCvmYuaSja3m1cKvBG_JNlW2LKz5ZZWLDChkhDSUajGQOTH13R6FhUmpBDeCBn1oi-I78BvHowwV3Dmj-VTHtjc-VlaqDzUlDOeJPXeSUV9td6sHUQiyiTPw4xS-OHQwqc_xqg7Ibs3eg1rtGGWjIByx9gvhWP3I5XBOUGCRR4XRX6JdBZ5gqTbFEeuDE4WphvFJE9WVViMyIvvXRTHJoE5mCBUq0d-iS_Y68Q5MVd_pQ0NlrrkE4ECWPH1mmUiDcIBYqmWmjN6Ns3FUKiKbCbn-CVXNI\x26sig\x3dCg0ArKJSzNk-ymgdsY3dEAE\x26urlfix\x3d1\x26adurl\x3d")

   
